qas.question: Who would prefix Sir, and Dames Grand Cross?

answers.text: Knights Grand Cross and Knights Commander

qas.question: Who would prefix Dame, to their forenames?
Who would prefix Lady to their surnames?
Such forms are not used by whom?
Who wouldn't use the title Sir of Dame?

answers.text: Clergy of the Church of England or the Church of Scotland

context: <a0_0>Knights Grand Cross and Knights Commander<a0_0/> prefix Sir, and <a1_0>Dames Grand Cross<a1_0/> and Dames Commander prefix Dame, to their forenames.[b] <a2_0>Wives of Knights<a2_0/> may prefix Lady to their surnames, but no equivalent privilege exists for husbands of Knights or spouses of Dames. Such forms are not used by <a3_0>peers and princes<a3_0/>, except when the names of the former are written out in their fullest forms. <a4_0>Clergy of the Church of England or the Church of Scotland<a4_0/> do not use the title Sir or Dame as they do not receive the accolade (i.e., they are not dubbed "knight" with a sword), although they do append the post-nominal letters.
